      <structure:Codelist id="CL_FREQ" agencyID="SDMX" version="2.0" isFinal="true">
        <common:Name xml:lang="en">Frequency</common:Name>
        <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides a set of values indicating the "frequency" of the data (e.g. weekly, monthly, quarterly). The concept “frequency” may refer to various stages in the production process, e.g. data collection or data dissemination. For example, a time
          series could be disseminated at annual frequency but the underlying data are compiled monthly. The code list is applicable for all different uses of "frequency". This code list was formally adopted on 4 December 2013. More information about and supporting material for this code list and
          SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address:
          https://sdmx.org/?page_id=4345.</common:Description>
        <structure:Code id="A">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Annual</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every year.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="S">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Half-yearly, semester</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every semester.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="Q">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Quarterly</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every quarter.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="M">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Monthly</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every month.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="W">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Weekly</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every week.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="D">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Daily</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every day.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="H">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Hourly</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used for data collected or disseminated every hour.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="B">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Daily – businessweek</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Similar to "daily", however there are no observations for Saturdays and Sundays (so, neither "missing values" nor "numeric values" should be provided for Saturday and Sunday). This treatment ("business") is one way to deal with such cases, but it is not the
            only option. Such a time series could alternatively be considered daily ("D"), thus, with missing values in the weekend.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="N">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Minutely</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">While N denotes "minutely", usually, there may be no observations every minute (for several series the frequency is usually "irregular" within a day/days). And though observations may be sparse (not collected or disseminated every minute), missing values do
            not need to be given for the minutes when no observations exist: in any case the time stamp determines when an observation is observed.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
      </structure:Codelist>
      <structure:Codelist id="CL_OBS_STATUS" agencyID="SDMX" version="2.1" isFinal="true">
        <common:Name xml:lang="en">Observation Status</common:Name>
        <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides coded information on 1) the quality of a value or 2) unusual or missing values. It was formally adopted on 15 September 2016. More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing
          general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.; syntaxes for the creation of further codes; general guidelines for the creation of SDMX code lists) can be found at this address: https://sdmx.org/?page_id=4345.</common:Description>
        <structure:Code id="A">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Normal value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">To be used as default value if no value is provided or when no special coded qualification is assumed. Usually, it can be assumed that the source agency assigns sufficient confidence to the provided observation and/or the value is not expected to be
            dramatically revised.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="B">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Time series break</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Observations are characterised as such when different content exists or a different methodology has been applied to this observation as compared with the preceding one (the one given for the previous period).</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="D">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Definition differs</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used to indicate slight deviations from the established methodology (footnote-type information); these divergences do not imply a break in time series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="E">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Estimated value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Observation obtained through an estimation methodology (e.g. to produce back-casts) or based on the use of a limited amount of data or ad hoc sampling and through additional calculations (e.g. to produce a value at an early stage of the production stage while
            not all data are available). It may also be used in case of experimental data (e.g. in the context of a pilot ahead of a full scale production process) or in case of data of (anticipated/assessed) low quality. If needed, additional information can be provided through free text using the
            COMMENT_OBS attribute at the observation level or at a higher level.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="F">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Forecast value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Value deemed to assess the magnitude which a quantity will assume at some future point of time (as distinct from "estimated value" which attempts to assess the magnitude of an already existent quantity).</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="G">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Experimental value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Data collected on the basis of definitions or (alternative) collection methods under development. Data not of guaranteed quality as normally expected from provider.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="H">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; holiday or weekend</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used in some daily data flows.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="I">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Imputed value (CCSA definition)</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Observation imputed by international organisations to replace or fill gaps in national data series, in line with the recommendations of the United Nations Committee for the Coordination of Statistical Activities (CCSA).</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="J">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Derogation</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Clause in an agreement (e.g. legal act, gentlemen's agreement) stating that some provisions in the agreement are not to be implemented by designated parties; these derogations may affect the observation or cause a missing value. In general, derogations are
            limited in time.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="K">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Data included in another category</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code is used when data for a given category are missing and are included in another category, sub-total or total. Generally where code "K" is used there should be a corresponding code "W - Includes data from another category" assigned to the over-covered
            category. Implementers and data reporters should use the COMMENT_OBS observation-level attribute to specify under which category the data are included.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="L">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; data exist but were not collected</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used, for example, when some data are not reported/disseminated because they are below a certain threshold.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="M">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; data cannot exist</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used to denote empty cells resulting from the impossibility to collect a statistical value (e.g. a particular education level or type of institution may be not applicable to a given country's education system).</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="N">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Not significant</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used to indicate a value which is not a "real" zero (e.g. a result of 0.0004 rounded to zero).</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="O">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code is to be used when no breakdown is made between the reasons why data are missing. Data can be missing due to many reasons: data cannot exist, data exist but are not collected (e.g. because they are below a certain threshold or subject to a
            derogation clause), data are unreliable, etc.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="P">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Provisional value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">An observation is characterised as "provisional" when the source agency - while it bases its calculations on its standard production methodology - considers that the data, almost certainly, are expected to be revised.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="Q">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Missing value; suppressed</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used, for example, when data are suppressed due to statistical confidentiality considerations.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="S">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Strike and other special events</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Special circumstances (e.g. strike) affecting the observation or causing a missing value.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="U">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Low reliability</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">This indicates existing observations, but for which the user should also be aware of the low quality assigned.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="V">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Unvalidated value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Observation as received from the respondent without further evaluation of data quality.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
        <structure:Code id="W">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Includes data from another category</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code is used when data include another category, or go beyond the scope of the data collection and are therefore over-covered. Generally, where code "W" is used there should be a corresponding code "K - Data included in another category" assigned to the
            category which is under-covered. Implementers and data reporters should use the COMMENT_OBS observation-level attribute to specify which additional data are included.</common:Description>
        </structure:Code>
      </structure:Codelist>
      <structure:Codelist id="CL_UNIT_MULT" agencyID="SDMX" version="1.1" isFinal="true">
        <common:Name xml:lang="en">Unit Multiplier</common:Name>
        <common:Description xml:lang="en">This code list provides code values for indicating the magnitude in the units of measurement. More information about this code list and SDMX code lists in general (e.g. list of generic codes for expressing general concepts like "Total", "Unknown", etc.;

    <structure:Concepts>
      <structure:ConceptScheme id="SDG_CONCEPTS" agencyID="IAEG-SDGs" version="1.0" isFinal="true">
        <common:Name xml:lang="en">SDG Concept Scheme</common:Name>
        <common:Description xml:lang="en">Concept Scheme for SDG Indicators</common:Description>
        <structure:Concept id="FREQ">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Frequency of observation</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Time interval at which observations occur over a given time period.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="REF_AREA">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Reference area</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Country or geographic area to which the measured statistical phenomenon relates.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="SEX">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Sex</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">State of being male or female.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="AGE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Age</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Length of time that an entity has lived or existed.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="EDUCATION_LEV">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Education level</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Highest level of an educational programme the person has successfully completed.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="OCCUPATION">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Occupation</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Job or position held by an individual who performs a set of tasks and duties.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="TIME_PERIOD">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Time period</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Timespan or point in time to which the observation actually refers.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="OBS_STATUS">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Observation status</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Information on the quality of a value or an unusual or missing value.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="OBS_VALUE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Observation value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Value of a particular variable.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="UNIT_MULT">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Unit multiplier</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Exponent in base 10 specified so that multiplying the observation numeric values by 10^UNIT_MULT gives a value expressed in the unit of measure.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="UNIT_MEASURE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Unit of measure</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Unit in which the data values are expressed.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="BASE_PER">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Base period</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Period of time used as the base of an index number, or to which a constant series refers.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="SERIES">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">SDG Series</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">SDG Indicator or Series. Uses the CETS convention for encoding.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="URBANISATION">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Degree of urbanisation</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Refers to Total, Urban, or Rural location.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="INCOME_WEALTH_QUANTILE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Income or wealth quantile</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Income or wealth quantile</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="CUST_BREAKDOWN">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Custom Breakdown</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Used to represent user-defined breakdowns.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="COMPOSITE_BREAKDOWN">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Composite breakdown</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Represents an amalgamation of infrequently used breakdowns.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="DISABILITY_STATUS">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Disability status</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Represents a person's disability status.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="NATURE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Nature of data points</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Information on the production and dissemination of the data (e.g.: if the figure has been produced by the country, estimated by an international agency, etc.)</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="TIME_DETAIL">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Time period details</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">When TIME_PERIOD refers to a date range, this attribute is used to provide metadata on the actual range the observation refers to (e.g. for period '2001-2003' TIME_PERIOD would be 2002 but the actual dates --2001-2003-- would be expressed
            here).</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="COMMENT_OBS">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Observation-level footnotes</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Additional information on specific aspects of each observation, such as how the observation was computed/estimated or details that could affect the comparability of this data point with others in a time series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="TIME_COVERAGE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Time period or range (ISO8601)</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">ISO8601 representation of the actual time interval to which the observation refers</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="UPPER_BOUND">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Upper bound value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Upper bound value for the indicator or series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="LOWER_BOUND">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Lower bound value</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Lower bound value for the indicator or series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="REPORTING_TYPE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Reporting type</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Represents whether the official SDG series is reported by a national, regional, or international agency.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="SOURCE_DETAIL">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Source details</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Information on the name and specific details of each observation's data source. Both the sources for the numerator and denominator could be specified here.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="ACTIVITY">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Economic activity</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Classification of economic activities</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="COMMENT_TS">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Time series-level footnotes</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Additional information on specific aspects applicable to all observations in the time series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="GEO_INFO_URL">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Geoinformation URL</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Location of geoinformation</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="GEO_INFO_TYPE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Geoinformation type</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Type of geionformation provided in attribute GEO_INFO_URL</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="CUST_BREAKDOWN_LB">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Label for custom breakdown</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Information provided in the CUST_BREAKDOWN dimension, when applicable</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="PRODUCT">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Type of product</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Type of product</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
        <structure:Concept id="DATA_LAST_UPDATE">
          <common:Name xml:lang="en">Date of the most recent change of the series.</common:Name>
          <common:Description xml:lang="en">Date of the most recent change of the series.</common:Description>
        </structure:Concept>
      </structure:ConceptScheme>
    </structure:Concepts>
